{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7a9612a1-bc4a-44f0-98fe-e7802f0a557f","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project itself is clean and minimal — the bottleneck isn't in what you're building, it's in **how** `dotnet build` is invoked. Each CLI invocation pays a cold-start cost: spinning up a new MSBuild process, evaluating the project graph, and running NuGet restore checks. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild nodes alive between builds.\n\n## Recommendations for Faster CLI Inner Loop\n\n**1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest impact)**\n\nThis keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive across builds, just like VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\n\nOr set it permanently in your shell profile. This eliminates the process startup cost on subsequent builds.\n\n**2. Use `dotnet watch` for edit-build-test cycles**\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nThis keeps the build process hot and watches for file changes — the closest CLI equivalent to the VS experience.\n\n**3. Skip restore when dependencies haven't changed**\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\nEach `dotnet build` runs an implicit `dotnet restore`. If your packages haven't changed, `--no-restore` shaves off the NuGet evaluation overhead.\n\n**4. Combine flags for maximum speed**\n\n```bash\nDOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1 dotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### Summary of expected impact\n\n| Technique | Saves | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| MSBuild Server | ~1-2s | Reuses MSBuild nodes across invocations |\n| `--no-restore` | ~0.5-1s | Skips NuGet dependency resolution |\n| `dotnet watch` | ~1-3s | Keeps process hot, skips startup entirely |\n\nNo project file changes are needed — these are all invocation-side improvements.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c4466045-9470-415f-8b3c-d872f7fdd069","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that CLI builds with `dotnet build` are slow for incremental builds, even when nothing has changed. Visual Studio builds almost instantly. The key insight from the developer report is:\n\n> The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThis is a well-known issue. The reason Visual Studio is faster is that it keeps the MSBuild process alive (it uses the MSBuild server/nodes that persist between builds). When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, each invocation starts a new MSBuild process, evaluates the project graph, and then determines nothing needs to be done.\n\n\nI can address this with a few approaches. The most practical is using `dotnet watch` for development workflows, which keeps the build process running and only rebuilds when files change. Alternatively, enabling MSBuild Server through environment variables or the `--tl` flag can help reuse MSBuild nodes across CLI invocations, reducing the startup overhead. Build Server** - `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between builds, which is the real performance win here. For the dev loop, `dotnet watch build` is ideal, and I should also mention `--no-restore` to skip the restore phase when dependencies haven't changed. The terminal logger with `--tl` can help too. Let me focus the response on these concrete, actionable optimizations that directly address the MSBuild startup overhead.","outputTokens":1165,"requestId":"C783:14D5C9:F0529A:12F461C:69FFD740"},"id":"ecb8bbe5-3b9e-4fe7-b7d6-db4cfb8bd220","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:48.781Z","parentId":"e7e59742-8b3a-42e9-9a3f-3206fbf65797"}
